<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="79">Hosts.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="79">
More than seven insect orders, including 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sorokin" authorityYear="1879" class="Sordariomycetes" family="Clavicipitaceae" genus="Metarhizium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="order">Coleoptera</taxonomicName>
(e.g. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Leach" authorityYear="1815" class="Insecta" family="Elateridae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" phylum="? arthropoda" rank="family">Elateridae</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1802" class="Hexapoda" family="Tenebrionidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Tenebrionidae</taxonomicName>
spp., 
<bibRefCitation author="Kabaluk, T" journalOrPublisher="IOBC / WPRS Bulletin" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" pagination="109 - 115" refId="B28" refString="Kabaluk, T, Goettel, M, Erlandson, M, Ericsson, J, Duke, G, Vernon, B, 2005. Metarhizium anisopliae as a biological control for wireworms and a report of some other naturally-occurring parasites. IOBC/WPRS Bulletin 28: 109 - 115" title="Metarhizium anisopliae as a biological control for wireworms and a report of some other naturally-occurring parasites." volume="28" year="2005">Kabaluk et al. 2005</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jip.2017.09.012" author="Kabaluk, T" journalOrPublisher="Journal of Invertebrate Pathology" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" pagination="82 - 87" refId="B29" refString="Kabaluk, T, Li-Leger, E, Nam, S, 2017. Metarhizium brunneum - an enzootic wireworm disease and evidence for its suppression by bacterial symbionts. Journal of Invertebrate Pathology 150: 82 - 87, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jip.2017.09.012" title="Metarhizium brunneum - an enzootic wireworm disease and evidence for its suppression by bacterial symbionts." url="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jip.2017.09.012" volume="150" year="2017">2017</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Humber, RA" journalOrPublisher="Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences, USA" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" publicationUrl="http://arsef.fpsnl.cornell.edu./" refId="B20" refString="Humber, RA, Hansen, KS, 2005. USDA-ARS Collection of Entomopathogenic Fungal Cultures (ARSEF), ARSEF-Index: Host by Fungus. http://arsef.fpsnl.cornell.edu./" title="USDA-ARS Collection of Entomopathogenic Fungal Cultures (ARSEF), ARSEF-Index: Host by Fungus." url="http://arsef.fpsnl.cornell.edu./" year="2005">Humber and Hansen 2005</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jip.2014.05.005" author="Reddy, GVP" journalOrPublisher="Journal of Invertebrate Pathology" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" pagination="43 - 49" refId="B70" refString="Reddy, GVP, Tangtrakulwanich, K, Wu, SH, Miller, JH, Ophus, VL, Prewett, J, Jaronski, ST, 2014. Evaluation of the effectiveness of entomopathogens for the management of wireworms (Coleoptera: Elateridae) on spring wheat. Journal of Invertebrate Pathology 120: 43 - 49, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jip.2014.05.005" title="Evaluation of the effectiveness of entomopathogens for the management of wireworms (Coleoptera: Elateridae) on spring wheat." url="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jip.2014.05.005" volume="120" year="2014">Reddy et al. 2014</bibRefCitation>
); inhabiting soil, plant surfaces and plant internal tissues (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1073/pnas.1412662111" author="Hu, X" journalOrPublisher="Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences, USA" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" pagination="16796 - 16801" refId="B19" refString="Hu, X, Xiao, G, Zheng, P, Shang, Y, Su, Y, Zhang, X, Liu, X, Zhan, S, St Leger, RJ, Wang, C, 2014. Trajectory and genomic determinants of fungal-pathogen speciation and host adaptation. Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences, USA 111: 16796 - 16801, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1073/pnas.1412662111" title="Trajectory and genomic determinants of fungal-pathogen speciation and host adaptation." url="https://doi.org/10.1073/pnas.1412662111" volume="111" year="2014">Hu et al. 2014</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.micres.2018.08.016" author="Bamisile, BS" journalOrPublisher="Microbiological Research" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" pagination="34 - 50" refId="B2" refString="Bamisile, BS, Dash, CK, Akutse, KS, Keppanan, R, Afolabi, OG, Hussain, M, Qasim, M, Wang, L, 2018. Prospects of endophytic fungal entomopathogens as biocontrol and plant growth promoting agents: an insight on how artificial inoculation methods affect endophytic colonization of host plants. Microbiological Research 217: 34 - 50, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1016/j.micres.2018.08.016" title="Prospects of endophytic fungal entomopathogens as biocontrol and plant growth promoting agents: an insight on how artificial inoculation methods affect endophytic colonization of host plants." url="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.micres.2018.08.016" volume="217" year="2018">Bamisile et al. 2018</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1080/09583157.2018.1531111" author="Brunner-Mendoza, C" journalOrPublisher="Biocontrol Science and Technology" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" pagination="83 - 102" refId="B7" refString="Brunner-Mendoza, C, Reyes-Montes, MDR, Moonjely, S, Bidochka, MJ, Toriello, C, 2019. A review on the genus Metarhizium as an entomopathogenic microbial biocontrol agent with emphasis on its use and utility in Mexico. Biocontrol Science and Technology 29 (1): 83 - 102, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1080/09583157.2018.1531111" title="A review on the genus Metarhizium as an entomopathogenic microbial biocontrol agent with emphasis on its use and utility in Mexico." url="https://doi.org/10.1080/09583157.2018.1531111" volume="29" year="2019">Brunner-Mendoza et al. 2019</bibRefCitation>
