<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="79">Widely distributed.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="79" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="79">Note.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="79">
<taxonomicName class="Sordariomycetes" family="Clavicipitaceae" genus="Metarhizium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Metarhizium anisopliae" order="Hypocreales" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="anisopliae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">Metarhizium anisopliae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species complex includes several cryptic species, for example, 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. anisopliae" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" rank="species" species="anisopliae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">M. anisopliae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Metschn.) 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Sorokīn">Sorokīn</normalizedToken>
, 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. brunneum" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" rank="species" species="brunneum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">M. brunneum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Petch and 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. robertsii" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" rank="species" species="robertsii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">M. robertsii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
J.F. Bisch., S.A. Rehner &amp; Humber (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.3852/07-202" author="Bischoff, JF" journalOrPublisher="Mycologia" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" pagination="512 - 530" refId="B6" refString="Bischoff, JF, Rehner, SA, Humber, RA, 2009. A multilocus phylogeny of the Metarhizium anisopliae lineage. Mycologia 101 (4): 512 - 530, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3852/07-202" title="A multilocus phylogeny of the Metarhizium anisopliae lineage." url="https://doi.org/10.3852/07-202" volume="101" year="2009">Bischoff et al. 2009</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.3852/13-319" author="Kepler, RM" journalOrPublisher="Mycologia" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" pagination="811 - 829" refId="B33" refString="Kepler, RM, Humber, RA, Bischoff, JF, Rehner, SA, 2014. Clarification of generic and species boundaries for Metarhizium and related fungi through multigene phylogenetics. Mycologia 106 (4): 811 - 829, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3852/13-319" title="Clarification of generic and species boundaries for Metarhizium and related fungi through multigene phylogenetics." url="https://doi.org/10.3852/13-319" volume="106" year="2014">Kepler et al. 2014</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.simyco.2020.04.001" author="Mongkolsamrit, S" journalOrPublisher="Studies in Mycology" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" pagination="171 - 251" refId="B61" refString="Mongkolsamrit, S, Khonsanit, A, Thanakitpipattana, D, Tasanathai, K, Noisripoom, W, Lamlertthon, S, Himaman, W, Houbraken, J, Samson, RA, Luangsa-ard, J, 2020. Revisiting Metarhizium and the description of new species from Thailand. Studies in Mycology 95: 171 - 251, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1016/j.simyco.2020.04.001" title="Revisiting Metarhizium and the description of new species from Thailand." url="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.simyco.2020.04.001" volume="95" year="2020">Mongkolsamrit et al. 2020</bibRefCitation>
). Amongst them, 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. brunneum" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" rank="species" species="brunneum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">M. brunneum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was most often noted as a wireworm pathogen (e.g. 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jip.2017.09.012" author="Kabaluk, T" journalOrPublisher="Journal of Invertebrate Pathology" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" pagination="82 - 87" refId="B29" refString="Kabaluk, T, Li-Leger, E, Nam, S, 2017. Metarhizium brunneum - an enzootic wireworm disease and evidence for its suppression by bacterial symbionts. Journal of Invertebrate Pathology 150: 82 - 87, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jip.2017.09.012" title="Metarhizium brunneum - an enzootic wireworm disease and evidence for its suppression by bacterial symbionts." url="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jip.2017.09.012" volume="150" year="2017">Kabaluk et al. 2017</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
